<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05019d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05019d">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05019d"> 19(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Numbers Chap V / (Water of the Lord</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> The priests made him <font color="green">[Joseph]</font> drink the <mark>&ldquo;water of the Lord,&rdquo;</mark> a beastly concoction which is described in the <mark>fifth chapter of Numbers</mark>. This water was warranted to cause rottenness in certain parts of guilty persons. But nothing happened to poor Joseph, who &ldquo;took Mary, and went home to his house, rejoicing and praising the God of Israel.&rdquo; <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) 173</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Numbers V deals primarily with jealousy and adultery, and proposes the use of a bowl of bitter water that (the offended husband hopes) will rot the thigh and swell the belly of a woman guilty of adultery. </mm> </dd></dl>
